[Local Tasks]        [Remote Tasks]
       ↓                    ↓
     Combine Task IDs (Union)
              ↓
      Compare Each Task
              ↓
   ┌───────────────┬───────────────┬───────────────┐
   │ Only Local    │ Only Remote   │ Both Exist    │
   │ → Send Remote │ → Send Local  │ → Resolve     │
   └───────────────┴───────────────┴───────────────┘
              ↓
      Conflict Resolution
 (Latest Update + Status + Tags)
              ↓
        Merged Tasks
              ↓
     Sync Updates (Both Sides)

def merge_tasks(local, remote):
    merged = {}

    all_ids = set(local.keys()) | set(remote.keys())

    for task_id in all_ids:
        if task_id in local and task_id not in remote:
            merged[task_id] = local[task_id]

        elif task_id in remote and task_id not in local:
            merged[task_id] = remote[task_id]

        else:
            # Conflict → latest wins
            if local[task_id]["updated"] > remote[task_id]["updated"]:
                merged[task_id] = local[task_id]
            else:
                merged[task_id] = remote[task_id]

    return merged


local_tasks = {
    1: {"name": "Task A", "updated": 5},
    2: {"name": "Task B", "updated": 3}
}

remote_tasks = {
    2: {"name": "Task B updated", "updated": 6},
    3: {"name": "Task C", "updated": 2}
}

print(merge_tasks(local_tasks, remote_tasks))
This algorithm reflects real-world synchronization systems, where data consistency must be maintained across multiple sources. Conflict resolution strategies such as “latest update wins” are essential in distributed systems.
